  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the rules/law of the custody of the children after divorcing in your country?",
  "response": "Custody laws vary significantly by country, and even within regions of the same country, so it's important to specify which country you are referring to. However, I can provide a general overview of commonly observed principles in many jurisdictions regarding child custody after divorce:\n\n1. **Types of Custody**: Custody is typically divided into two main types:\n   - **Legal Custody**: Refers to the right to make important decisions about the child's life, including education, health care, and religious upbringing.\n   - **Physical Custody**: Refers to where the child lives on a day-to-day basis.\n\n2. **Types of Arrangements**:\n   - **Sole Custody**: One parent has both legal and physical custody of the child.\n   - **Joint Custody**: Both parents share legal and/or physical custody. This can be joint legal custody, where they both make decisions for the child, or joint physical custody, where the child spends significant time with both parents.\n\n3. **Best Interests of the Child**: Most jurisdictions prioritize the child's best interests when determining custody arrangements. Factors that may be considered include:\n   - The child's age and developmental needs.\n   - The emotional ties and relationships with each parent.\n   - The ability of each parent to provide a stable and loving environment.\n   - Any history of abuse or neglect.\n\n4. **Visitation Rights**: If one parent has sole custody, the other parent may be granted visitation rights. These rights can be scheduled and structured, or in some cases, may be flexible.\n\n5. **Mediation and Court Proceedings**: Many jurisdictions encourage or require parents to participate in mediation before going to court to resolve custody disputes. If mediation fails, the case may go to court.\n\n6. **Modification of Custody**: Custody agreements can sometimes be modified if there is a significant change in circumstances, such as one parent moving or changes in the child's needs.\n\n7. **Child Support**: In addition to custody, divorce proceedings typically address child support, which is financial support provided by one parent to the other for the child's living expenses.\n\nFor specific rules and regulations, it\u2019s best to consult a legal expert or family law attorney in your jurisdiction, as they can provide tailored information based on local laws.",
